[1] Red ring and threat of lethal yellowing - Colombia, Ecuador
Date: September 2010
Source: International Centre for Tropical Agriculture (CIAT) newsletter
[edited]
<http://webapp.ciat.cgiar.org/newsroom/e_newsletter/newsletter_08/enews08_story3.htm>


Colombia prepares for coconut "disease squeeze"
-----------------------------------------------
The spread of the devastating red ring disease in the south of the country
and in neighboring Ecuador, combined with the threat in the north from the
spread of the virulent lethal yellowing disease from Central America, means
coconut producers are facing an assault on 2 fronts.

Red ring disease has already killed up to 80 per cent of coconut palms in
the south western departments of Narino and Cauca. In some of the areas you
can see field after field of palm stumps. Now experts fear that it is only
a matter of time before lethal yellowing disease, which has already killed
millions of coconut palms across Mexico, Honduras, and Jamaica, reaches
South America.

CIAT, with USAID, the Yucatan Center for Scientific Research (Mexico), and
national organizations, are developing methods for rapid testing for
resistance to red ring disease and are also investigating possible genetic
resistance to lethal yellowing in the tall [variety] palms native to Mexico.

--
communicated by:
Hugh Harries
Editor, Google Coconut Group
<http://groups.google.com/group/coconut?hl=en>

